[normal]Summary[bold]              
[normal]There is little that is markedly new in AR5
[normal] WGI 
[normal]Summary for Policy Makers
[normal] (other than the IPCC is at last beginning to consider long
[normal]er
[normal]-term business-as-usual scenarios
[normal] in the main body of the text
[normal]).  AR5 largely affirms (and in this sense strengthens) AR4
[normal]'s conclusions
[normal]. 
[normal]AR5 is a staging post in charting the on-going progress of
[normal] climate change science.
[normal] There are areas of future concern that do deserve further attention
[normal] such as the possibility of crossing a climate threshold (critical transition)
[normal].  There is also a presentational issue of comparing forecasts across the sweep of IPC
[normal]C Assessments.
[normal]  Separately, t
[normal]here is a policy-driven research issue that might fall between DECC and DEFRA stools
[normal]: that of the need for species translocation protocols to manage carbon and biological conservation due to climate change driven biome shift
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
