[normal]              
[normal]Select Committee question:[bold] 
[normal]How effective is AR5 and the summary for policymakers in conveying what is meant by 
[normal]uncertainty in scientific terms
[normal]? Would a focus on risk rathe
[normal]r than uncertainty be useful?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]26)
[normal]              
[normal]R
[normal]isk is more the province of WG II and III
[normal]              
[normal]Uncertainty
[normal] has always been difficult to convey outside of science and statisticians.  The IPCC has come up with a system that conveys uncertainty as well as might
[normal] for policy-ma
[normal]kers
[normal]. A focus on 'risk' would be decidedly out of place in WG
[normal] 
[normal]I.  
[normal]'
[normal]Risk
[normal]'
[normal] implies that there is something being risked and hence that there are 
[normal]'
[normal]stakes
[normal]'
[normal] and 'hazard'
[normal].  This takes us into the realm of degree of 
[normal]'
[normal]impacts
[normal]'
[normal] and 
[normal]'
[normal]likelihood thereof
[normal]'
[normal],
[normal] and this is firmly the province of WG II.
[normal]  There is a difference between 'certainty' (or 'probability'), 'risk' and hazard'.  (I am likely to be able to walk ten feet along a joined twin line of bricks laid on the ground without much problem.  However if 
[normal]this two line of bricks was part of a tall
[normal], two-brick wide,
[normal] wall then though (psychology aside) I may still be able to walk it with the same 
[normal]'
[normal]certainty
[normal]'
[normal], the 
[normal]'
[normal]hazard
[normal]'
[normal] if I came off would be much greater.)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Select Committee question: 
[normal]Can any of the areas o
[normal]f the science now be considered settled as a result of AR5’s publication, if so which? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]27)
[normal]              
[normal]Areas settled
[normal]              
[normal]The IPCC's assessments as a whole (1990-2013) portray a clear picture that:
[normal]-
[normal]i
[normal])    The Earth is currently warming
[normal]ii)   The Earth's climate has chan
[normal]ged in the past
[normal]iii)  Climate change has a major impact on natural systems (on which we depend) 
[normal]iv) Current warming is largely due to human activity and the trajectory is unprecedented in human history leading to more
[normal] intense extreme weather events
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Polic
[normal]y-makers should consider t
[normal]hese matters 
[normal]settled
[normal].
[normal]  It is therefore worrying that a still few members of either side of both Houses
[normal] in 
[normal]Westminster
[normal] do not accept 
[normal]the policy-maker (UN) created scientific consensus (IPCC) view.  If these policy-makers will not 
[normal]accept this view, on what authority are they basing their decisions?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]28)
[normal]              
[normal]Good to see long-term business-as-usual forecasts beginning to be considered
[normal]              
[normal]There are a number of new areas of science in the main body of the IPCC text yet to be approved.  I was 
[normal]pleased to see
[normal] (in the draft of chapter 12)
[normal] consideration of RCP 
[normal]8.5 which is 
[normal]effectively continued 
[normal]long-term 
[normal]reliance on fossil fuel
[normal]s (
[normal]including more expensive fossil fuels such as tar sand
[normal]s) beyond the 21st century, as this is the trajectory we are curre
[normal]ntly on (we have yet to begin to stabilise greenhouse emissions and these are still increasing) and policy-makers do need to know where we
[normal] are heading
[normal] if we fail to 
[normal]act 
[normal]decisively. This long-term projection depicts a median temperature rise of around 8°C b
[normal]y 2150 (and I am not sure if this includes permafrost and methane 
[normal]clathrate
[normal] positive feedback
[normal]s
[normal], if not then this warming will be more 
[normal]severe, and if it does
[normal] 
[normal]include
[normal] feedbacks
[normal] this
[normal] 8°C
[normal] is more than severe enough to completely disrupt
[normal] the
[normal] current 
[normal]pattern of 
[normal]agricultural systems globally).  The IPCC has to date been reluctant to look at such a long-term, business-as-usual type scenario.  This I suspect has been because it has not wanted to be overly alarmist and back in 1990 (its first assessment) it 
[normal]possibly 
[normal]did not consider that a quarter of a century on we would still be on its (1990) business-as-usual trajectory.
