[normal]Select Committee question:[bold] 
[normal]What areas need further effort to reduce the levels of uncertainty?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]29)
[normal]              
[normal]W
[normal]eather and climate hence computers and 
[normal]Earth system modelling need continued effort
[normal]              
[normal]The exact degree of warming and the nature of weather and weather patterns in a warmer world needs further elucidation.  This requires better modelling, both 
[normal]via
[normal] understanding of the Earth system and model exec
[normal]ution which require
[normal]s
[normal] improved computer technology.  The models themselves require increased resolution and improved biological components (including bio-geological components such as soil an
[normal]d marine carbon biosphere res
[normal]ervoirs
[normal]).
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Currently the race to impr
[normal]ove computer technology and climate models is more or less neck and neck and is likely to continue with
[normal] research
[normal] investment as is.
[normal]  This is a long-term venture and polic
[normal]y-makers need to realise that w
[normal]ith this research we are likely in for the long-haul wit
[normal]h incremental progress continually being made
[normal] over the years
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]30)
[normal]              
[normal]Solar monitoring
[normal]              
[normal]Of lesser concern, solar monitoring is also required and here much is already
[normal] being done or research
[normal] 
[normal]is 
[normal]in train.  However here it will be a while before we have a suffici
[normal]ently long record before 
[normal]major 
[normal]solar uncertainties 
[normal]can be reasonably 
[normal]assessed
[normal].
[normal]  Having said that (and I should say that here I am looking outside my own area of interest and over the shoulders of others), it is unlikely that solar influence will hugely aff
[normal]ect the broad warming trajectory in the long-term 
[normal]we currently foresee, 
[normal]but it might affect decadal warming
[normal] adding a ripple to the longer-term warming trend
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]31)
[normal]              
[normal]Earth system science and crossing critical transitions needs more attention
[normal]              
[normal]What is importan
[normal]t is Earth system (biosphere science) research. 
[normal]Earth system understanding in turn requires continued long-term monitoring and, importantly, improved 
[normal]thermal 
[normal]monitoring of deep seas and abyssal depths.  It also requires better 
[normal]und
[normal]erstanding of 
[normal]palaeoclimat
[normal]es
[normal].  Here t
[normal]he probability of flipping to a new climate state also needs to be considered
[normal] should the Earth
[normal] system
[normal] go through a 'critical transition'
[normal] and cross a climate threshold
[normal].  
[normal]With this in mind, 
[normal]AR4 
[normal](WG I, 2007, pp442-3, in chapter 8, 
[normal]Palaeoclimate
[normal], section 6.3.3) 
[normal]drew attention to the similarities of what we are doing now with what are known as carbon isotope excursion events especially that of the early Eocene 55 million years ago
[normal] (known as the IETM
[normal] or PETM)
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Back then
[normal] it seems as if 
[normal]vulcanic
[normal] greenhouse gas warmed the Earth so inducing the release of organic carbon 
[normal](12-carbon rich) 
[normal]from biosphere reservoirs which enhanced the warming further 
[normal]via
[normal] a positive feedback loop.
[normal] This warming event was 
[normal]initia
[normal]ted within a few centuries, and saw temperature
[normal] rise
[normal], sea level rise, ocean acidification and marked biome (ecosystem assemblages) shift
[normal] 
[normal]pol
[normal]e
[normal]wards
[normal], for around 100,000 years.  Furthermore, we know from carbon isotope (13C/12C) analysis 
[normal]broadly
[normal] the amount of
[normal] 12-carbon isotope rich greenhouse gas involved
[normal],
[normal] and as AR4 noted this was 
[normal]of a
[normal] similar 
[normal]order of magnitude 
[normal]to the amount of carbon we will have likely emitted since the industrial revolution and the end of this century unless radical actions are taken to c
[normal]urb greenhouse gas emissions.
[normal]  It is therefore a shame that the ambition laid out in 
[normal]Agreed Reference Material For The IPCC Fifth Assessment Report
[normal] (2009) that AR5 would see ' [
[normal]Palaeoclimate
[normal]] Abrupt climate changes and their regional expression'
[normal],
[normal] as well a
[normal]s '
[normal]Palaeoclimate
[normal] perspective on irreversibility in the climate system'
[normal],
[normal] was not realised.  Had it been realised AR5 would have most likely seen a further assessment of the PETM / IETM literature as well as that on critical transitions
[normal] and climate threshold
[normal]s
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]32)
[normal]              
[normal]There is a possible policy gap between DECC and DEFRA policy-driven research, an example being managing species shift for both biological conservation and carbon management purposes
[normal]              
[normal]A little beyond the scope of this consultation, but nonetheless r
[normal]elated, is the question of ecological shift.  Given global warming will be inevitable in the absence of major cuts in emissions
[normal] as the WG I 
[normal]Summary for Policymakers 
[normal]makes clear,
[normal], species' range
[normal]s
[normal] will shift.  Yet with some ecosystems (such as woodland) taking many decades to establish, there is a very strong case for species transloca
[normal]tion along climate gradients.  Yet c
[normal]urrently there are no formally agreed protocols for such translocation.  Nor ar
[normal]e their formal networks of dialogue between nature reserves along climate gradients nationally and internationally 
[normal]to
[normal] manage species and ecosystem migration
[normal],
[normal] as well as
[normal] maintaining
[normal] carbon-related ecosystem function
[normal] in addition to biological conservation
[normal].  
[normal]I mention this now as there is concern that some research and policy discussion may fall between DECC and DEFRA stools.  As climate-chang
[normal]e
[normal]-driven species translocation is climate change, and carbon, related it could be argued as to fall under DECC's purvie
[normal]w. 
[normal]Conversely,
[normal] as 
[normal]these are
[normal] to do with environmental conservation it could be seen as the responsibility of DEFRA.  
[normal]Consequently,
[normal] I flag this issue now for your attention.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]33)
[normal]              
[normal]Future IPCC forecast portrayals need to be standardised and compared with past 
[normal]B-a-U forecasts
[normal]              
[normal]Each IPCC Assessment has a graph of warming projections over the 21st century.  Here the date the projections commence vary from assessment to assessment and there is no sense given as to how these compare with previous Assessment projecti
[normal]ons. 
[normal]What I would like to see
[normal] 
[normal]in the next IPCC Assessment WG I report (AR6) is for the warming projections to commence from 1990 as that is a key policy date. I would also like to see
[normal] additionally
[normal] a graph of all the IPCC business-as-usual scenarios and the
[normal]ir SRES and RCP analogues from the various Assessments 
[normal](1990-2013 
[normal]etc
[normal]) 
[normal]all on the same graph.  I have actually done this for the assessments up to and including AR4 (2007) and they all fall within the upper and lower estimates for the IPCC 1990 business-as
[normal]-usual scenario: they are (un)surprisingly similar and should lend confidence as to the continuation of message.
