[normal]              [bold]Select Committee question:[bold] 
[normal]Has AR5 sufficiently explained the reasons behind the widely reported hiatus in the global surface temperature 
[normal]record?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]34)
[normal]              
[normal]Pause not yet satisfactorily explained
[normal]              
[normal]I have not (yet) come across a detailed examination of this question in AR5 (but this may be because I have not read the whole 
[normal]draft 
[normal]WG I 
[normal]volume 
[normal]thoroughly
[normal])
[normal].  
[normal]Speaking personally, i
[normal]t should be said that we cannot say exactly why the global surface record has 
[normal]ceased to show an overall warming trend the past one-and-a-half decades since near the end of the 20th century.  Having said that
[normal],
[normal] this 'pause' is not that particularly unexpecte
[normal]d and th
[normal]ere a
[normal]re a number of possible explanations
[normal] for it
[normal].  It is 'not unexpected' because we have had pauses before. The period from 1940 – 1980 was a previous pause.  
[normal]Yet
[normal], because there is now more anthropogenic greenhouse gas in the atmosphere today comp
[normal]ared to back then, and 
[normal]because
[normal] atmospheric greenhouse concentrations are continuing to rise, we might expect this current pause to be shorter.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]35)
[normal]              
[normal]The long pause was predicted
[normal]              
[normal]Furthermore, this pause is not only 
[normal]'
[normal]not unusual
[normal]'
[normal] it was actually predicted by
[normal] at least one team half a decade ago that the then short warming pause would continue (Yu 
[normal]Kosaka
[normal] &amp; Shang-Ping 
[normal]Xie
[normal], 2008, 
[normal]Nature
[normal] 
[normal]501,[bold] 403-7). They predicted that the N. Atlantic would cool as would the Pacific. 
[normal](Their reasons 
[normal]hypothesised 
[normal]were 
[normal]weather/clima
[normal]te
[normal] cycle and 
[normal]Broecker
[normal] global 
[normal]thermohaline
[normal] circulation related.)
[normal] 
[normal]They said
[normal] that such cooling may be so great as to impede the current warming trend.  They.. 
[normal]"
[normal]conclude that the recent cooling of the tropical Pacific and hence the current hiatus are probably 
[normal]due to natural internal variability rather than a forced response. If so, the hiatus is temporary, and global warming will return when the tropical Pacific swings back to a warm state. Similar hiatus events may occur in the future..
[normal]."  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]36)
[normal]              
[normal]The question 
[normal]of importance is where has the heat gone?
[normal]              
[normal]More recently other work points to the El Niño cycle (again the Pacific
[normal] related
[normal])
[normal] as the cause of the pause
[normal].  There are other 
[normal]explanations that
[normal] may or may not have a significant bearing on the problem and these inc
[normal]lude our lack of 
[normal]a spatially 
[normal]detailed long-term Arctic record.  Irrespectively, the hiatus in the global surface temperature record does not undermine the IPCC consensus view.
[normal]  Here t
[normal]he 
[normal]real 
[normal]issue of concern is what has happened to the 'missing' heat?  The
[normal] obvious suggestion is that this has gone into the oceans and this is worrying as 
[normal]that
[normal] will eventually lead to marine methane 
[normal]clathrate
[normal] destabilization
[normal] with the release of methane and additional warming above and beyond that incurred by direct human emissi
[normal]ons
[normal].
