[normal]Select Committee question:[bold] 
[normal]What implications do the IPCC’s conclusions in the AR5 Physica
[normal]l Science Basis report have for policy making both nationally and internationally? 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]38)
[normal]              
[normal]AR5 affirms previous assessments' policy relevance
[normal]              
[normal]The implications are that since AR4 (2007) new science affirms previous understanding, that current unaltered 
[normal]emission trends remain on an unfavourable trajectory
[normal], and that we may well exceed the 2°
[normal]C so-called 'safe' warming limit
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]39)
[normal]              
[normal]Irrespective of climate change, medium-to-log-term finite fossil fuel economics necessitate weaning off of fossil carbon.
[normal]              
[normal]At thi
[normal]s point I would like to take leave of the IPCC and draw the Committee
[normal]'
[normal]s attention to the implications of the world continuing its addiction to fossil carbon.  Irrespective of climate change concerns, fossil fuel consumption is increasing.  Yet we all know too well that fossil fuels are finite.  The cheap fossil fuel 
[normal]reserves
[normal] go
[normal] first
[normal] leaving more expensive reserves
[normal] for later use
[normal].  This drives up prices.  World population is
[normal] also
[normal] growing and so demand for fossil fuel rises. This too drives up prices.  
[normal]These 
[normal]different 
[normal]increased pressures on price act synergistically. 
[normal]The long-t
[normal]erm, real-term cost of fossil fuel is 
[normal]inevitably 
[normal]set to increase.  It is therefore in nations' interests to switch to non-fossil fuel energy
[normal] irrespective of climate change arguments
[normal]. 
[normal](This 
[normal]case
[normal] 
[normal]was
[normal] at the heart of 
[normal]Climate and Human Change: Disaster or Oppo
[normal]rtunity?
[normal], 1998, back when climate change denial was stronger than it is today
[normal].
[normal])
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]Only short-termism gives any grounds for not cold-
[normal]Turkeying
[normal] from fossil fuel.
[normal]  Delaying
[normal] 
[normal]matters by kicking the issue into the long grass simply makes things worse for future g
[normal]enerations.
[normal]  Add back in IPCC climate concerns and it really is inexcusable
[normal] (arguably 
[normal]a wanton dereliction of duty
[normal])
[normal] in terms of both national and global interest
[normal] for policy-makers
[normal] to
[normal] avoid
[normal] act
[normal]ing
[normal].
[normal]  (See also the Stern report on the economics of climate cha
[normal]nge.)
