[normal]              
[normal]Select Committee question: [bold]Is the IPCC process an effective mechanism for assessing scientific knowledge? Or has it focussed on providing a justification for political commitment?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]41)
[normal]              
[normal]There is more than a little 
[normal]post hoc ergo propter hoc
[normal] about this question.  Let us be clear, policy-makers (those concerned with political commitment) through the United Nations (UN) called for 
[normal] 
[normal]i
[normal].
[normal] an assessment of climate change science, and
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]ii
[normal]. formulation of realistic response strategies.  The UN in turn
[normal] called 
[normal]upon
[normal] two of its agencies (the UN Environment Programme and World Meteorological
[normal] Organiz
[normal]ation
[normal]) to establish the IPCC and this they did in 1988.  That the IPCC has provided a sufficiently clear picture
[normal],
[normal] that demonstrates that political commitment is 
[normal]warranted
[normal],
[normal] is neither a failing of the IPCC nor an indication that there is some sort of bias.  Climate change has been an issue on 
[normal]the formal agenda of the World's political leaders at least since 1972 and the UN Conference on the Human Environment that y
[normal]ear.  Since then climate change has formally been on the political agenda at the UN level as well as to varying degrees on the national-level agenda of a number of 
[normal]UN
[normal] member states.  The IPCC itself does not define what political action should be taken: it
[normal] simply
[normal] provides information.  That climate change is an issue of political concern precedes the IPCC and was the reason for it
[normal]s formation
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]42)
[normal]              
[normal]Try replacing 'the IPCC process' and 'it' in the question with 'evidence gathering' and it is clear that the qu
[normal]estion is one of 
[normal]post hoc ergo propter hoc
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]43)
[normal]              
[normal]Is 'evidence gathering' an effective mechanism for assessing scientific knowledge? Or has 'evidence gathering' focussed on providing a justification for political commitment?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]44)
[normal]              
[normal]The alternative is that pol
[normal]icy should not be evidence-based.
